<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/5042431-kelly"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1585220977i/5042431._UY100_CR2,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/5042431-kelly">Kelly</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">It clearly did disturb the Massies, but at the same time, to fire her would have meant that they had to put their jobs on hold to look for someone els<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">It clearly did disturb the Massies, but at the same time, to fire her would have meant that they had to put their jobs on hold to look for someone else. It would have disrupted life. She cooked, cleaned and took care of the children. It was easier and more desireable to turn a blind eye. I think a lot of the novel was focused on career vs. children. Myriam put her career before her children, and coincidentally, so did Louise. I'm a working mother myself, but in both cases within the novel, the "job" was the most important thing and how each woman measured their success.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

